    <!-- SCIENCE SECTION -->
    <h2 id="science">The Science Behind Shilajit: What Research Actually Shows</h2>

    <p>Shilajit has been studied extensively in both Ayurvedic pharmacology and modern clinical research. Unlike many trending supplements, it has a legitimate body of peer-reviewed evidence supporting specific physiological effects — though the scope of that evidence varies significantly by health claim.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Testosterone: strong evidence</strong>
        <p>Two RCTs (2015, 2016) in Andrologia demonstrated significant increases in total and free testosterone in both healthy and infertile men at 250mg/day over 90 days.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Mitochondrial energy: moderate evidence</strong>
        <p>A 2012 study showed shilajit upregulates CoQ10 levels in skeletal muscle, increasing ATP production by enhancing electron transport chain efficiency.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Cognitive protection: emerging evidence</strong>
        <p>Fulvic acid inhibits tau protein aggregation in vitro (Journal of Alzheimer's Disease, 2011). Human trials are ongoing but preliminary data is encouraging.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Iron absorption: moderate evidence</strong>
        <p>Shilajit's fulvic acid enhances iron bioavailability by acting as an ionic mineral transporter, supporting hemoglobin synthesis in iron-deficient populations.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3>Testosterone: The Landmark Studies</h3>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>A 2016 RCT in <em>Andrologia</em> enrolled <strong>96 healthy men aged 45-55</strong> and administered 250mg of purified shilajit (PrimaVie) daily for 90 days. Results: total testosterone increased by <strong>20.45%</strong>, free testosterone by <strong>19.14%</strong>, and DHEA-S by <strong>31.35%</strong> — all statistically significant compared to placebo.</p>
      <cite>Andrologia, 2016 — 96 participants, 90-day RCT</cite>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>A complementary 2015 study in <em>Andrologia</em> evaluated shilajit in <strong>60 infertile men</strong> over 90 days. Total sperm count increased by <strong>61.4%</strong>, sperm motility improved by <strong>12.4%</strong>, and testosterone levels rose by <strong>23.5%</strong>. These are clinically meaningful improvements in male reproductive health markers.</p>
      <cite>Andrologia, 2015 — 60 participants, 90-day RCT</cite>
    </div>

    <h3>Energy, Recovery, and Athletic Performance</h3>

    <div class="vs-strip">
      <div class="vs-item">
        <strong>CoQ10 Synergy</strong>
        <p>Shilajit + CoQ10 increased mitochondrial CoQ10 by 29% vs. CoQ10 alone<br /><em>J Int Soc Sports Nutr, 2012</em></p>
      </div>
      <div class="vs-item">
        <strong>ATP Production</strong>
        <p>Enhanced electron transport chain efficiency measured in skeletal muscle tissue<br /><em>J Ethnopharmacol, 2012</em></p>
      </div>
      <div class="vs-item">
        <strong>Exercise Recovery</strong>
        <p>Reduced muscle damage markers (CK, LDH) post-exercise in trained athletes<br /><em>J Int Soc Sports Nutr, 2019</em></p>
      </div>
