    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Shilajit Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is shilajit and where does it come from?</summary>
      <p>Shilajit is a sticky, tar-like resin that seeps from high-altitude rocks in the Himalayas, Altai Mountains, and Caucasus ranges at elevations between 1,000 and 5,000 meters. It forms over centuries from the slow decomposition of plant matter compressed between layers of rock. The resulting substance is rich in fulvic acid, humic acid, and over 85 trace minerals. It has been used in Ayurvedic medicine for more than 3,000 years as a rejuvenating tonic known as a <em>rasayana</em>.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What does fulvic acid in shilajit do?</summary>
      <p>Fulvic acid is the primary bioactive compound in shilajit, typically comprising 60 to 80 percent of purified shilajit by weight. It acts as a potent electrolyte and mineral transporter, enhancing cellular absorption of nutrients across the gut lining. Research published in the <em>Journal of Alzheimer's Disease</em> found that fulvic acid inhibits tau protein aggregation, a hallmark of neurodegenerative disease. It also exhibits strong antioxidant properties, neutralizing free radicals and reducing oxidative stress at the mitochondrial level.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can shilajit gummies increase testosterone?</summary>
      <p>A 2016 randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled study published in <em>Andrologia</em> found that 250mg of purified shilajit (PrimaVie) taken daily for 90 days increased total testosterone by 20.45% and free testosterone by 19.14% in healthy men aged 45 to 55. A separate 2015 study in the same journal showed similar results in infertile males. However, these studies used purified, standardized shilajit — results may vary with non-standardized products that do not disclose their fulvic acid content.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Is shilajit safe to take every day?</summary>
      <p>Purified shilajit at doses of 200 to 500mg per day has been used safely in clinical trials lasting up to 90 days. A 2019 safety study in the <em>Journal of Medicinal Food</em> found no adverse effects on liver enzymes, kidney function, or blood markers at 500mg daily for 12 weeks. However, raw or unpurified shilajit may contain heavy metals, mycotoxins, or other contaminants. Only use products that have been purified and third-party tested for heavy metal content. Start with the lowest recommended dose and increase gradually.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Why is shilajit trending on TikTok?</summary>
      <p>Shilajit has accumulated over 500 million views on TikTok, driven by fitness influencers and biohacking communities promoting it for energy, testosterone support, and athletic recovery. The viral trend accelerated in late 2024 when several prominent creators documented 30 and 90 day supplementation protocols, reporting improved energy levels, workout performance, and mental clarity. The gummy format has further boosted mainstream accessibility by eliminating the strong mineral taste of traditional shilajit resin, which many consumers find unpalatable.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the difference between shilajit resin and shilajit gummies?</summary>
      <p>Traditional shilajit resin is a concentrated, tar-like substance dissolved in warm water or milk before consumption. It offers the highest potency per serving but has a strong, bitter, mineral taste that many find unpleasant. Gummies use purified shilajit extract standardized for fulvic acid content, combined with sweeteners and flavoring for palatability. The trade-off is that gummies typically contain lower doses per serving (200 to 500mg versus 300 to 600mg for resin) and include additional inactive ingredients. For most consumers, the improved compliance of gummies outweighs the marginally higher potency of resin.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How long does it take for shilajit to work?</summary>
      <p>Most users report noticeable improvements in energy and mental clarity within one to two weeks of consistent daily use. The testosterone and hormonal effects documented in clinical trials were measured at the 90-day mark, indicating that meaningful hormonal changes require sustained supplementation over at least three months. Mitochondrial energy production improvements, based on CoQ10 synergy research, may begin within two to four weeks. Consistency is essential — sporadic use will not produce the results observed in controlled studies.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can women take shilajit gummies?</summary>
      <p>Yes. While shilajit is often marketed toward men for testosterone support, its benefits extend to both sexes. The fulvic acid, trace minerals, and antioxidant properties support energy production, iron absorption, and mitochondrial function regardless of gender. A 2012 study in the <em>Journal of Ethnopharmacology</em> found that shilajit reduced fatigue and improved cellular energy in both male and female subjects. Women who are pregnant or breastfeeding should avoid shilajit due to insufficient safety data in these populations.</p>
    </details>

